	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Quantifying the impact of non-tariff measures: A case study in maximum residue levels</h1>

			
			<h4>
												13 October 2013
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>A World Bank Group research paper entitled ‘The effect of product standards on agricultural exports from developing countries’ has sought to quantify the effect of maximum residue levels (MRLs) on exports from developing countries. It reviews data on MRLs for 61 countries and, using macro-economic modelling techniques, seeks to quantify “the impact that food standards have on international trade in agricultural products”.</p><p>The analysis found that “more restrictive standards in a destination market result… in fewer firms exporting into this market.” The analysis also found that “exporters in low income countries are more adversely affected by stricter standards”, since “firms need to comply with importers’ standards which impose a fixed cost to firms that need to adjust their production processes in order to meet those foreign standards.” This is more expensive for developing country producers that have lower standards on their domestic markets. However, the analysis noted that “meeting stringent standards increases primarily the fixed costs of exporting” but that “once firms enter the market… standards do not impact the level of exports.”</p><p>The analysis argued that “regulatory standards are sometimes more prescriptive or restrictive than they need to be” to achieve the desired health and safety goals. In addition, “differing requirements between countries can result in substantial additional costs for producers and the exclusion of foreign firms from markets.”</p><p>The analysis significantly notes that “higher income countries are generally known for having stricter standards,” and on this basis warns that as the Brazilian, Russian, Indian and Chinese (BRIC) economies become more affluent it is likely that “their standards for food will also be tightened…, effectively shutting out certain LDC exports from these growing markets.” In this context it was noted that developing countries have recently been submitting more notifications on sanitary and phytosanitary (SPS) measures to the WTO than developed economies.</p><p>The analysis argued that “in order for developing countries to take advantage of new opportunities, [they] need to be aware of their supply side constraints including their infrastructure and institutions in order not to be shut out of these markets.”</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>World Bank, ‘The effect of product standards on agricultural exports from developing countries’, WPS6518, 28 June 2013</p><p>
<a href="http://econ.worldbank.org/external/default/main?pagePK=64165259&amp;theSitePK=469372&amp;piPK=64165421&amp;menuPK=64166093&amp;entityID=000158349_20130628082952" target="_self">http://econ.worldbank.org/external/default/main?pagePK=64165259&amp;theS...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>While the World Bank analysis represents a valuable attempt to quantify the impact of MRLs on developing countries’ exports, it does not capture the dynamic nature of the application of standards, with the manner of application often being as important as the basic standards established (see <i>Agritrade</i> articles ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Commodities/Horticulture/New-EU-maximum-residue-levels-hit-Kenyan-vegetable-exports" target="_blank">New EU maximum residue levels hit Kenyan vegetable exports</a>’, 28 April 2013, ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Topics/SPS-Food-safety/Tightening-of-Citrus-Black-Spot-controls-could-pose-challenges" target="_blank">Tightening of Citrus Black Spot controls could pose challenges</a>’, 28 April 2013, ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Commodities/Beef/Commercial-implications-of-EU-SPS-requirements-hinder-development-of-smallholder-beef-supplies-in-Namibia" target="_blank">Commercial implications of EU SPS requirements hinder development of sma...</a>’, 4 May 2013).</p><p>The importance of establishing dialogue structures and multilateral guidelines on how standards are applied in practice is given increased significance by the World Bank analysis, which suggests that, as BRIC economies become more affluent, their food safety standards will become increasingly strict. This potentially carries significant consequences for ACP exporters, particularly LDC members of the ACP group.</p><p>Getting to grips with how standards are applied to ACP–EU agro-food sector trade could therefore be a sound basis for meeting the food safety and SPS challenges faced in diversifying trade towards the faster growing economies of the BRICs (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Topics/SPS-Food-safety/The-growing-importance-of-non-tariff-measures" target="_blank">The growing importance of non-tariff measures</a>’, 7 October 2013).</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
